description:
File: internal/server/authoring_handler.go, line 86

The ErrSpecAlreadyExists handler passes the raw wrapped error to connect.NewError:

  if errors.Is(err, storage.ErrSpecAlreadyExists) {
      return nil, connect.NewError(connect.CodeAlreadyExists, err)
  }

Because err is the fully wrapped chain from runInTxOrSequential, the client-visible message is: 'transaction: create spec: slug "foo": spec already exists'. This exposes internal implementation details (layer prefixes, slug value in error chain, memgraph query path names).

The project's established convention, enforced throughout stageError, is to pass a fresh errors.New() string to avoid leaking internals. All other sentinel mappings follow this pattern:

  return connect.NewError(connect.CodeNotFound, errors.New("spec not found"))
  return connect.NewError(connect.CodeFailedPrecondition, errors.New("spec is already approved"))

The CLAUDE.md explicitly states: 'Handler error sanitization — stageError and similar methods sanitize internal errors before returning to clients.'

Suggested fix:

  if errors.Is(err, storage.ErrSpecAlreadyExists) {
      return nil, connect.NewError(connect.CodeAlreadyExists, errors.New("spec with this slug already exists"))
  }

Note: the handler unit test (TestAuthoringHandler_Spark_AlreadyExists) only asserts the error code, not the message, so this leak is not caught by existing tests.

internal/storage/memgraph/findings.go ListFindings (line ~83-167) performs a MATCH query against HAS_FINDING edges. If the spec does not exist, the MATCH simply returns zero records and the function returns an empty slice with nil error — it never calls GetSpec and never returns ErrSpecNotFound.

The handler in internal/server/analytical_pass_handler.go (lines 154-157) checks:
  if errors.Is(err, storage.ErrSpecNotFound) {
      return nil, connect.NewError(connect.CodeNotFound, err)
  }

This branch is dead code: the storage layer will never surface ErrSpecNotFound from ListFindings. Callers asking for findings on a typo'd or deleted spec receive HTTP 200 with an empty findings array instead of HTTP 404. This makes it impossible to distinguish 'spec exists but has no findings' from 'spec does not exist', which will cause silent misbehavior in agents that rely on this distinction.

Fix: add a spec-existence check at the start of ListFindings (call GetSpec and return ErrSpecNotFound if not found), mirroring the pattern already used by StoreFindings.

A companion test TestListFindings_SpecNotFound is also missing from both the handler test and the integration test.

cmd/specgraph/docs.go, the writeGroups function (line ~141 in the new file):

  if !written[c.Name()] && c.Name() != "help" && c.Name() != "completion" && c.Name() != "docs" {

The exclusion of 'docs', 'help', and 'completion' from the Other catch-all section has no comment. A future maintainer adding a new meta-command may not understand why these are excluded, or may need to add another command to the exclusion list.

Suggested fix: Add a brief comment:
  // Skip meta-commands that are not useful in the CLI reference.
  if !written[c.Name()] && c.Name() != "help" && c.Name() != "completion" && c.Name() != "docs" {

File: internal/storage/findings.go, FindingsReader interface (lines ~1989-1992 in diff).

The FindingsWriter interface method StoreFindings has a clear doc comment explaining the replace-not-append semantics and return value. The companion FindingsReader.ListFindings method has no doc comment at all.

This is notable because the empty-passType behavior (return all findings for the spec) is a non-obvious semantic contract that callers need to know about. The memgraph implementation documents it in its own function comment, but the interface — which is what callers depend on — is silent.

Suggested fix: Add a comment to the interface method:
  // ListFindings returns findings for slug, filtered to passType if non-empty.
  // An empty passType returns all findings across all pass types.
